image.alt_text: Photo by Toomer’s Corner Sit-In on November 26, 2021. May be an image of text.
image.caption:
#Day543 of the #greattoomerscornersitin & we observed 43 positive interactions on the second #thanksgiving holiday spent on the corner! 

#ToomersSitIn #season6 - Day 543 #thanksgiving2021 

• 43 positives 🙌❤️’s
• No negatives

Today on Toomer’s Sit-In: 

- Rev. Darcy and Andrew take on the Corner this thanksgiving day so Damarius and Kelli can enjoy a day off with their loved ones. They are happy to bless, those who so often give until their cup is empty. We’re so grateful to have a team of folks to keep this going running like this ❤️🙏🌸 

- In keeping with our theme and the day, Darcy made signs reminding us of our Native family who suffered much due to the bad faith agreements and broken promises of White colonists and settlers. She began the two hours with a prayer for the Muskogee people in exile on whose ancestral homeland we sit every day. One of her signs today brings attention to the many native children who go missing in this country with little to no resources available to help find them. 

- It’s a quiet day downtown, but families are enjoying the unseasonably warm weather. Many smile and wave, wishing us a Happy Thanksgiving. Speaking of family, two beloved members of the All Souls’ Church family stop by the corner to exchange hugs and words of peace and love. Darcy and Andrew discuss the menus of their respective dinners awaiting them at the end of the day. 

- Halfway through the afternoon, Darcy prayed The Litany, a solemn prayer said in her faith tradition at times of sorrow, crisis, tragedy, or penitence, on Facebook live with her congregation. Around her neck was a purple scarf, a color representing penitence and contrition in her church. Those walking by were unsure of what she’s doing and maybe even waiting for her to tell them they are going to hell like so many other clergy on this corner. But that is not Darcy’s ministry— she’s a no hell minister, not a hell no minister! ❤️

- No negatives!!!!

Updating the #year2 big board: 77,436 positives & 768 negatives. 

#StopRacismNow #BLM #KeepGoing #KeepAbortionLegal #civildiscourse #ToomersCorner #Auburn #Alabama #muskogeeland #belovedcommunity #mmiw #nativelivesmatter

The first every Missing and Murdered Indigenous Women and Girls Event is being held on February 14, 2022 at Street Angels. 

The event will start at 1:00pm with an opening prayer, cedar , and smudging, followed by a March through Cranbrook. Upon the return to Street Angels there will be a self defence demonstration by Rocky Mountain Martial Arts, drumming & more. *we are still in the planning stage, so more details will be shared soon*

The aim of the event is to stand up against violence, and honour the missing sisters who never returned home.

image.alt_text: Photo by Shop Jada // Jaimie Davis art in Laxyuubm Ts’msyen - Tsimshian Territory - Terrace, BC. May be an image of outdoors and text that says 'MMW 4AN matriarchsintraining'.
image.caption:
Posted @withregram • @matriarchsintraining "The first women’s memorial march was held in 1992 in response to the murder of a woman on Powell Street in Vancouver. Out of this sense of hopelessness and anger came an annual march on Valentine’s Day to express compassion, community, and caring for all women in Vancouver’s Downtown Eastside on unceded Coast Salish territories.

The memorial march continues to honour the lives of missing and murdered women, and all women’s and gender-diverse peoples’ lives lost in the Downtown Eastside. Increasing deaths of many women and gender-diverse people from the DTES still leaves family, friends, loved ones, and community members with an overwhelming sense of grief and loss. Indigenous women, girls, two spirit and trans people disproportionately continue to go missing or be murdered with minimal to no action to address these tragedies or the systemic nature of gendered violence, poverty, racism, or colonialism." 
(womensmemorialmarch.wordpress.com)

Join us February 14 at noon, Terrace City Hall as we hold space for our murdered and missing Kin. Event link is in our bio ❤

#MMIWG2S #MMIW #MMIMB #MMIWawareness #HighwayOfTears #nomorestolensistersandbrothers

image.alt_text: Photo by Ashley Lynn Esthetics in Ashley Lynn Esthetics. May be an image of 1 person and standing.
image.caption:
Missing And Murdered Indigenous Women 
It’s not talked about enough. It’s something that hits close to home to me because I am Native. Please read as this means a lot to me:

May 5th is MMIW awareness day. Yes it’s a couple months away but I want to start working on this and start spreading awareness. Those who want to help spread awareness that day with the “No More Stolen Sisters” picture” I will provide the red paint and take the photo of you in my studio so you can post it on your social media May 5, 2022 to help spread awareness. 

If you’re still with me and reading, thank you:

Why is it so important to spread awareness? 

Here’s just a few facts:
Eight days.
That’s how long it took to find Gabby Petito. 

When Rae Elaine Tourtillott, an 18-year-old member of the Menominee tribe, disappeared in 1986, it took authorities six months to locate her. When 22-year-old Katelyn Kelley went missing, it was nine months before her remains were found.

The government is so quick to tell native people to be quiet or silence us. 

5,712 known cases of missing or murdered native women in 2016. Only 116 were LOGGED in the DOJ database. Since 2016 we’ve lost count. 

Most cases did NOT happen on reservation land. 

I think about it all the time how I could have been one of these statistics. When I was a child I was almost kidnapped. I remember all the details of the situation. 

67% the number of cases between 2005-2009 the US attorney declined to prosecute involving sexual abuse. 

96% of the cases on some reservations the number of sexual violence against native women were committed by non-natives. 

A picture is worth a thousand words. Help bring awareness that we don’t want to be silenced anymore…so we don’t have anymore stolen sisters. 

Photo used is not mine but to reference what no more stolen sisters looks like of what would be taken of you. 

#MMIW #MMIWawareness #MMIWday #NoMoreStolenSisters #NativePride

image.alt_text: Photo by Brianna on January 11, 2022. May be a closeup of one or more people.
image.caption:
Since the time of first contact, our women have been sexualized, fetishized and disrespected because of our beautiful auburn skin. Out of fear and survival instincts my sisters have been taught to cover their feminine features. “Respect your bodies or no one else will.” This is a survival strategy forced by colonial images of my people and their beautiful women. 

These photos might offend and I understand why... but this is my power. I am a woman, It is my right to be proud of my feminine features. I am an Indigenous woman, it is my right to be proud of my skin colour. I am no longer scared, the fear of the past doesn’t control my projections of myself any longer. I am strength and resilience. 

Photographer: @indigenality_photography 

#indigenouswomen #mmiw #strength #beauty #power #indigenous #history #nativewomen #womenempowerment #future #awareness #rise

image.alt_text: Photo by Women Of The White Buffalo on January 09, 2022. May be an image of 4 people and text.
image.caption:
🚨We are introducing Spotlight Sunday with Sun Rose where, every week, she will be interviewing and highlighting activists, artists and individuals who are both Native and non-Native, and who are doing important work for Indigenous communities all around the world.

Sun Rose Iron Shell, from Women Of The White Buffalo, will be going live today with Lydia Ponce, an Indigenous Mayo & Quechua, Peace and Environmental Advocate based in Los Angeles California. She created MMIWLA.org and also presented it to the Pacifica National Radio Board to create national programming for MMIW to list information and updates, searches, policies and resources on national radio platforms to work in unity with relatives and to find relatives.

📍Join us today at 3PM PST // 6PM EST on our Instagram page!

🙏Please head to the website and Facebook page to help shape and amplify this important opportunity to end modern day femicide and genocide. 

☝️Links in bio

🌎The organisation tackles, and is in line with, some of the United Nations Sustainable Development Goals, which provides a shared blueprint for peace and prosperity for people and the planet, now and into the future:

5. Gender equality
10. Reduced inequalities
16. Peace, justice and strong institutions
